    value: 무제(武帝)가 살았을 때에, 주공(周公)이 어린 성왕(成王)을 업고 제후의 조회를 받는 그림을 곽광에게 주어 어린 소제(昭帝)를 보호해 줄 것을 부탁하였음. 《한서 곽광전(漢書霍光傳)》
english:
  title: On Huo Guang
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When one can serve the public good while simultaneously pursuing private family interests, the heart is not rooted in true Goodness. In judging a person, we must not look at what they struggle to cultivate, but rather at what they neglect. One who strives in public matters yet disregards private concerns—such a person I have observed in Huo Guang.

    Confucius said: "One who can be entrusted with a young orphan, entrusted with the fate of a province, and who cannot be swayed when facing great trials—is such a person not a true gentleman? Yes, truly a gentleman." Mencius said: "The Good extend their love from those they cherish to those they do not; the ungood extend their indifference from those they dislike even to those they love." Thus Huo Guang may be called a gentleman, yet lacking in Goodness.

    Huo Guang served the Martial Emperor, received the trust of guardianship over a young sovereign, and bore the burden of the realm. He established the Young Emperor and served as his regent. Shang Guan An was Huo Guang's nephew. An's father, Shang Guan Jie, had risen to the Nine Ministers under the previous reign and held rank above Huo Guang. When father and son both became generals and gained the favor of the imperial household—the empress being An's own daughter and Huo Guang her grandfather—he wielded sole authority over court affairs, causing conflict between them.

    Thus Jie and An conspired with Sang Hong Yang, forging a letter from the King of Yan to present as if from a tributary mission. Yet the Young Emperor's wisdom discerned the deception. Later, when someone among Jie and An's faction slandered Huo Guang, the emperor grew angry, saying: "Huo Guang was entrusted by the late emperor to protect my person. Let any who speak ill of him be punished." From then, Jie's faction dared not speak further. The Long Princess arranged a banquet, invited Huo Guang, laid an ambush to kill him, deposed the emperor, and attempted to enthrone the King of Yan. When discovered, Huo Guang had Jie, An, and Sang Hong Yang all executed; the King of Yan and the Princess took their own lives. Though this was their own doing, Huo Guang had cultivated the conditions for it.

    When the sovereign is young and the realm uncertain, Jie and An's plot to remove Huo Guang threatened all under Heaven. Yet the false letter originated with the King of Yan—cause enough for suspicion and removal. Jie's faction's slander was grave deceit of the throne—cause enough for banishment. Had the Young Emperor not merely proclaimed punishment but actually executed it, the Shang Guan calamity would have been prevented and the family spared. Thus even Huo Guang's strategy came too late.

    In the first year of Yuanping, the emperor died without heir. Huo Guang invited the King of Changyi, He, and enthroned him. Once seated, He indulged in depravity. Huo Guang grew troubled until Tian Yan Year urged him: "Did the ancients ever do such a thing?" "Yes," replied Yan, "Yi Yin served the Shang, deposed the too-wayward Tai Jia to preserve the state, and later ages praised his loyalty. Should you do likewise, general, you would be the Yi Yin of Han."

    Huo Guang sent him back to the King's residence, saying: "The king has severed himself from Heaven's will. We cannot repay his kindness with our lives, yet I dare not betray the state." Thus Huo Guang established the heart for Heaven and Earth, opened the great peace for endless ages—worthy to stand beside Yi Yin himself. Without awaiting Yang Chang's memorial, the Han realm had already passed into the Xuan Emperor's hands through succession.

    Huo Guang elevated and enthroned the Xuan Emperor. The emperor, before ascending, had heard of the Huo clan's overwhelming power and harbored ill feeling. Later, riding in the imperial chariot with Huo Guang, he felt as a thorn pricked his back. Once he took direct command of affairs, the Grand Commandant Wei Xiang and the Imperial Attendant Xian grew deeply resentful of the Huo family. The emperor established Xu as empress, but Xian favored his younger daughter Cheng Jun and wished to place her instead. He secretly instructed the physician Chunyu Yan to poison Empress Xu, then urged Huo Guang to adopt Cheng Jun as the new empress.

    Jie and An's downfall had stemmed from establishing an empress—a lesson Huo Guang should have heeded. Instead, unknowingly becoming like Jie and An, he repeated their error. What heart could this reflect? When Xian feared exposure, he confessed everything. With Xian already having poisoned the mother of all under Heaven and installed his daughter as empress, what should Huo Guang have done? He should have reported Xian's crimes in detail; then the state's law would have operated of itself. Yet with all his loyalty, Huo Guang did nothing, remaining silent to the end. Thus the Spring and Autumn annals praise the great principle that sacrifices even kinship, while the Han histories record the dark conspiracy of a wicked wife. How can two cases of identical character yield such opposite responses?

    After Huo Guang's death, the matter gradually came to light. Huo Yu and others wept together, blaming themselves, and plotted to depose the emperor. When discovered, Yun Shan took his own life, Yu was cut in two at the waist, Xian and his siblings were executed in the marketplace, and thousands of families connected to the Huo clan perished. The catastrophe exceeded even that of Jie and An. A family must first destroy itself before others destroy it. Thus Huo Guang destroyed his own house.

    Huo Guang, lacking education and learning, knew not how to govern his family with propriety or bestow genuine affection. What he called showing kindness merely disrupted order and kinship—deservedly, his line faced obliteration. This is what Mencius meant: extending what one dislikes even to what one loves.

    Goodness means possessing impartiality and rectitude. Though the heart may spring from public concern, achieving true rectitude is most difficult. Huo Guang, moved by the Martial Emperor's gift of the Zhou Duke's portrait, alone bore the weight of the realm's safety and the state's survival or fall. Through apt decisions on deposing and enthroning, he rekindled the Liu flame when it had nearly died and recovered the Han throne when it seemed lost. Surely he deserves the name loyal minister. Yet whether his heart, springing from public service, achieved true rectitude remains unknowable.

    For more than a thousand years since the Han, there have been many loyal ministers and righteous servants, none comparable to Huo Guang. Yet the subtle workings of his heart cannot go unexamined. Thus I say: Huo Guang was a gentleman, yet lacked true Goodness.
  footnotes:
    - The 'portrait of the Zhou Duke' refers to an image of the Duke of Zhou holding the young King Cheng and receiving the homage of the feudal lords—given by the Martial Emperor to Huo Guang as a charge to protect the young Zhao Emperor (from the Records of Huo Guang in the History of Han).
